Alpha (uppercase , lowercase ; , √°lpha, modern pronunciation √°lfa) is the first letter of the Greek alphabet. In the system of Greek numerals, it has a value of 1.
It was derived from the Phoenician and Hebrew letter aleph - an ox or leader.
Letters that arose from alpha include the Latin A and the Cyrillic letter –ê.
In English, the noun "alpha" is used as a synonym for "beginning", or "first" (in a series), reflecting its Greek roots.Uses
